      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The Late Bronze Age collapse was caused by a systemic failure of the interdependent palatial trade and diplomacy network, triggered by a cascade of disruptions that the redistributive palace economies were too rigid to absorb.\", \"mechanism\": \"Palaces operated as centralized hubs for collection, storage, and redistribution of agricultural surplus and luxury goods, and for organizing long-distance trade. This created a tightly coupled system where a shock to one node (e.g., crop failure, earthquake, or trade route disruption) would cascade through the network. When multiple shocks hit simultaneously, the administrative and economic complexity of the palaces became a liability: they could not adapt quickly enough, leading to a loss of faith in the elite, abandonment of the palaces, and a systemic collapse of the entire Eastern Mediterranean network.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Evidence of a single, simultaneous military conquest across all regions by a unified external enemy (e.g., a single 'Sea Peoples' army).\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Evidence that all affected regions experienced identical, simultaneous, and total environmental catastrophes (e.g., a single mega-drought) with no regional variation.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Egypt survived because its geography (the Nile) provided a more resilient agricultural base and a more unified state structure that could absorb shocks and repel the disparate 'Sea Peoples' migrations, which were a symptom, not the root cause, of the systemic collapse.\"}",
